nodes.bodyText:
Example: v.map(...).find(..)
The return value of map is Vec.  DDlog returns by-value, so we need to create a fully populated vector before passing it to the next transformer (find).
Let's say, we change map to return Iterator<> instead. The iterator object would internally hold a reference to the original vector v.  This is safe as long as the iterator is destroyed before anyone tries to modify or destroy v, which is the case here. But not in this code:
var iter = v.map();
v.push(x);
iter.find(...);

In Rust this cannot happen thanks to the borrow checker.  In fact, the above code will be rejected by the Rust compiler.  But DDlog does not currently have a way to track ownership.

